text: Why does almost every single sequel completely miss what made the first movie any good, and instead double down on the truly inconsequential fluff?  The action in the first Equalizer was a sideshow. It was not the main attraction. The main attraction was that he was so mysteriously confident and never actually even came close to losing or even being an underdog. The dramatic curve was thrown  out of the window - he won, then he won some more, then won everything. Doing that again will probably not be a good idea, but not even acknowledging that this was what made it unique and "good" is mind boggling to me.
